                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d549">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">561.35E1/68: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-03-10T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 10, 1934—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>95. For Atherton: Your 108, March 8, noon. Although this Government recognizes
                    the importance of regulating the disposal of surplus crops, it will not be in a
                    position to undertake any commitment regarding them until Congress has acted on
                    the sugar bill now before it.</p>
                <p>Your position with regard to disposal of initial Philippine surplus is
                    approved.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
